Abstract

This project aims to predict the 5-day ahead market direction of the NIFTY 50 using interpretable machine learning techniques. 
Historical daily price data from 2010–2024 was collected and transformed into log returns and technical indicators. 
A classification framework was developed where the target variable represents the future direction of returns. 
Logistic Regression, Decision Tree, and Random Forest models were implemented and evaluated using a time-series train-test split. 
Model performance was assessed using accuracy, precision, recall, and ROC-AUC metrics. 
A trading strategy based on model predictions was constructed to evaluate economic usefulness. 
The strategy performance was compared with the market using cumulative returns, Sharpe ratio, and drawdown analysis. 
Interpretability techniques such as feature importance and SHAP values were applied to understand model behavior. 
The results indicate that machine learning models provide slight improvements over baseline models but remain close to random prediction levels. 
The study highlights the presence of weak predictability in financial markets and emphasizes the importance of interpretability in model-driven decision making.
